Fig.ç6. 
<taxonomicName id="E9D34D4AFFE9FF83E8B700D1FE0B0DBA" authority="Saba &amp; Iwao &amp; Fujita, 2012" authorityName="Saba &amp; Iwao &amp; Fujita" authorityYear="2012" box="[217,463,944,966]" class="Asteroidea" family="Asterinidae" genus="Disasterina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="subSpecies" species="isasterina" status="sp. nov." subSpecies="akajimaensis">
<emphasis id="1CA7EADBFFE9FF83E8B700D1FE0B0DBA" box="[217,463,944,966]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">D isasterina akajimaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="079457A0FFE9FF83E9BB00D0FDDD0DBA" box="[469,537,944,965]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, holotype (NSMT E-6758). Schematic view of oral plate pair and interradial uncalci ed area. Abbreviations: fs, furrow spine; iua, interradial uncalci ed area; op, oral plate; os, oral spine; sas, subambulacral spine; tm, thin membrane; tp, thin plate.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="2E6C36C9FFE9FF83E8DB063AFD810B8C" blockId="6.[156,767,1077,2077]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">
Superomarginal plates minute, 
<quantity id="E92B9B2CFFE9FF83E99B0639FDF30B0D" box="[501,567,1369,1394]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.524" metricValueMax="1.778" metricValueMin="1.27" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" unit="in" value="6.0" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="5.0">5–7 in</quantity>
number, not forming distinct series. Inferomarginal plates 
<quantity id="E92B9B2CFFE9FF83EA28061AFD660BED" box="[582,674,1402,1426]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.254999999999999" metricValueMax="8.89" metricValueMin="7.62" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" unit="in" value="32.5" valueMax="35.0" valueMin="30.0">30–35 in</quantity>
number, arranged in series; spatulate, each bearing transverse distal fringe of 3 (rarely 2 or 4) webbed sacciform spinelets (Fig. 3F). Terminal plates roundish rectangular.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2E6C36C9FFE9FF83E8DB069CFDCE082A" blockId="6.[156,767,1077,2077]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">
Papulae large, isolated, and present only on abactinal surface; numerous (
<quantity id="E92B9B2CFFE9FF83E924057DFE44084A" box="[330,384,1565,1589]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0668" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" unit="in" value="42.0">42 in</quantity>
number) in central pentagonal area, sparse in radial part of ray (Fig. 3C).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2E6C36C9FFE9FF83E8DB053EFD4A08C9" blockId="6.[156,767,1077,2077]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">On actinal surface, interradial uncalci ed area present just distal to oral plate pair, covered with thin membrane in which 3 small, thin plates embedded (Figs 3D, 6).</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2E6C36C9FFE9FF83E8DB05DFFEB40946" blockId="6.[156,767,1077,2077]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Each oral plate bearing 4–5 oral spines; lacking suboral spines (Figs 3D, E, 6). Oral spines arranged closely in curved line; webbed basally by thin membrane; inner 3 spines longer than outer 1 or 2.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2E6C36C9FFE9FF83E8DB0422FC0F0AF2" blockId="6.[156,767,1077,2077]" lastBlockId="6.[820,1432,1077,2077]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">
Adambulacral plates 
<quantity id="E92B9B2CFFE9FF83E9E40422FE270925" box="[394,483,1857,1882]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.636" metricValueMax="8.89" metricValueMin="8.382" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" unit="in" value="34.0" valueMax="35.0" valueMin="33.0">33–35 in</quantity>
number, each with 3 (rarely 1 or 2) glassy furrow spines webbed by thin membrane, and 1 long, glassy subambulacral spine (Figs 3E, 6). Actinolateral plates roughly arranged in longitudinal rows; those of innermost two rows larger, each bearing long, sacciform actinolateral spine and innermost one extending just before terminal plate; outer rows unarmed, strongly imbricated (Fig. 3E). Most of oral spines, furrow and subambulacral spines, and actinolateral spines with 1–3 small transparent terminal teeth (Fig. 4B).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2E6C36C9FFE9FF83EB2007F6FB810B70" blockId="6.[820,1432,1077,2077]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Superambulacral plates present irregularly, very small (Fig. 5C). Superactinal plates consisting of a single plate, present at internal margin, numerous interradially, becoming fewer distally (Fig. 5B).</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2E6C36C9FFE9FF83EB200678FC240B2E" blockId="6.[820,1432,1077,2077]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Color in life uniformly light brown abactinally, whitish actinally (Fig. 2).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="66C96542FFE9FF83EB20063AFA4A0946" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="2E6C36C9FFE9FF83EB20063AFB920967" blockId="6.[820,1432,1077,2077]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis id="1CA7EADBFFE9FF83EB20063AFC6F0B0D" bold="true" box="[846,939,1370,1394]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Remarks</emphasis>
.Thi s specimen was recorded as a young form of 
<taxonomicName id="E9D34D4AFFE9FF83EB3D061BFC390BED" authorityName="Liao" authorityYear="1980" box="[851,1021,1402,1426]" class="Asteroidea" family="Asterinidae" genus="Disasterina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="odontacantha">
<emphasis id="1CA7EADBFFE9FF83EB3D061BFC390BED" box="[851,1021,1402,1426]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">D. odontacantha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in our preliminary report (
<bibRefCitation id="4A424B38FFE9FF83ED47061AFCA10BCC" author="Saba, M. &amp; Iwao, K. &amp; Fujita, T." pageId="6" pageNumber="27" pagination="18 - 24" refId="ref4896" refString="Saba, M., Iwao, K. and Fujita, T. 2008. Report on the asteroid fauna around Akajima Island, Kerama Islands, Okinawa, Japan. Midoriishi 19: 18 - 24, Report of Akajima Marine Science Laboratory." type="journal article" year="2008">
<collectingCountry id="56C47659FFE9FF83ED47061AFA9C0BED" box="[1321,1368,1402,1426]" name="Bonaire, Sint Eustatius and Saba" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Saba</collectingCountry>
<emphasis id="1CA7EADBFFE9FF83ED0D061BFA5C0BED" box="[1379,1432,1402,1426]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">et al.</emphasis>
2008
</bibRefCitation>
). The present new species is closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="E9D34D4AFFE9FF83ED5106FBFC4F0BAC" authorityName="Liao" authorityYear="1980" class="Asteroidea" family="Asterinidae" genus="Disasterina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="odontacantha">
<emphasis id="1CA7EADBFFE9FF83ED5106FBFC4F0BAC" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">D. odontacantha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as well as 
<taxonomicName id="E9D34D4AFFE9FF83EB9006DCFB4A0BAC" authorityName="Perrier" authorityYear="1875" box="[1022,1166,1467,1491]" class="Asteroidea" family="Asterinidae" genus="Disasterina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="abnormalis">
<emphasis id="1CA7EADBFFE9FF83EB9006DCFB4A0BAC" box="[1022,1166,1467,1491]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">D. abnormalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, both of which share low and at arms without a median keel, and a conspicuous interradial uncalci ed area. It is closer to 
<taxonomicName id="E9D34D4AFFE9FF83ECA7069DFAAB086B" authorityName="Liao" authorityYear="1980" box="[1225,1391,1532,1556]" class="Asteroidea" family="Asterinidae" genus="Disasterina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="odontacantha">
<emphasis id="1CA7EADBFFE9FF83ECA7069DFAAB086B" box="[1225,1391,1532,1556]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">D. odontacantha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but distinguishable by the absence of spinelets on most abactinal plates in contrast to the presence of the 1–2 spinelets, and by the 4 or 5 closely placed oral spines without any gap between them, in contrast to 3 or 4 more widely spaced spines. It is also distinguishable from 
<taxonomicName id="E9D34D4AFFE9FF83EC0205C0FB3E08C8" authorityName="Perrier" authorityYear="1875" box="[1132,1274,1695,1719]" class="Asteroidea" family="Asterinidae" genus="Disasterina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="abnormalis">
<emphasis id="1CA7EADBFFE9FF83EC0205C0FB3E08C8" box="[1132,1274,1695,1719]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">D. abnormalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the absence of a suboral spine on each oral plate in contrast to the presence of a long, sacciform one. The di erences from the other species are shown in 
<tableCitation id="63510372FFE9FF83EC660460FB940966" box="[1032,1104,1792,1817]" captionStart="Tableç" captionStartId="1.[150,198,841,864]" captionTargetBox="[171,2017,976,1442]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Tableç1.C haracteristics of the species of Disasterina. N: number of specimens recorded. R, r: body size (R,r) in mm. R in parentheses is shown without r. R/r: R/r ratio. Body: L=low and at, H=high with median keel on rays. IUA: interradial uncalci ed area, P=present, A=absent. ABS: number of abactinal spinelets. SMS: number of superomarginal spinelets. IMS: number of inferomarginal spinelets. ALS: number of actinolateral spines. OS: number of oral spines. SOS: number of suboral spines. FS: number of furrow spines. SAS: number of subambulacral spines. Numbers in parentheses for ABS and IMS are observed for only several particular plates. Asterisks (*) indicate type locality." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/7AAC6641FFEEFF84E8F80029FC950DCB" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" tableUuid="7AAC6641FFEEFF84E8F80029FC950DCB">Table 1</tableCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2E6C36C9FFE9FF83EB200441FA4A0946" blockId="6.[820,1432,1077,2077]" box="[846,1422,1825,1850]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">This is the rst report of this genus from Japanese waters.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="66C96542FFE9FF83EB200421FB730905" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="2E6C36C9FFE9FF83EB200421FB730905" blockId="6.[820,1432,1077,2077]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis id="1CA7EADBFFE9FF83EB200421FC170926" bold="true" box="[846,979,1857,1881]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Distribution</emphasis>
.On ly from the 
<typeStatus id="F168886BFFE9FF83ECE30422FB7D0925" box="[1165,1209,1858,1882]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">type</typeStatus>
locality, Akajima, the Ryukyu Islands, 
<collectingCountry id="56C47659FFE9FF83EBB40403FBD60905" box="[986,1042,1891,1914]" name="Japan" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Japan</collectingCountry>
(present study).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="66C96542FFE9FF82EB2004E3FEAA0F40" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="28" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="2E6C36C9FFE9FF82EB2004E3FEAA0F40" blockId="6.[820,1432,1077,2077]" lastBlockId="7.[156,767,197,320]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="28" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis id="1CA7EADBFFE9FF83EB2004E3FC0509E4" bold="true" box="[846,961,1923,1947]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Etymology</emphasis>
.Th e speci c epithet 
<taxonomicName id="E9D34D4AFFE9FF83ECC304E3FAE909E4" authorityName="Saba &amp; Iwao &amp; Fujita" authorityYear="2012" box="[1197,1325,1923,1947]" class="Asteroidea" family="Asterinidae" genus="Disasterina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="akajimaensis">
<emphasis id="1CA7EADBFFE9FF83ECC304E3FAE909E4" box="[1197,1325,1923,1947]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">akajimaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is derived from the island of Akajima, where the 
<typeStatus id="F168886BFFE9FF83ECB204C3FAF109C4" box="[1244,1333,1955,1979]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">holotype</typeStatus>
was collected. New Japanese names given for this genus and species are Numeri-itomaki-hitode-zoku and Akajima-numeriitomaki-hitode, respectively. Akajima is the locality, while in Japanese “numeri” refers to the slimy nature of the body surface, an “itomaki” is a spool used in sewing with a shape that looks like asterinid sea stars, “hitode” are seastars, and “zoku” means genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
